{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522060"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:40:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:40:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13796"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13796"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.62,0.01,0.13,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6413"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49997"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6413"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13796"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35250"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"837"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1393"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12632"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12633"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42937"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44551"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49997"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to his General Practice with a six-month history of progressive anorexia and weight loss. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears cachectic and mildly distressed. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Examination reveals visible dilated, tortuous veins on his upper chest, neck, and face. These veins become more prominent when the patient lies flat. There is also mild facial swelling and plethora. His abdomen is soft and non-tender with no palpable hepatomegaly or splenomegaly. There are further dilated veins running longitudinally along his abdominal wall (image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Portal hypertension","Superior vena cava obstruction","Cushing\u0027s syndrome","Budd-Chiari syndrome","Congestive heart failure"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture described is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior vena cava obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E. The key features are the presence of dilated, tortuous veins on the upper chest, neck, and face, which become more prominent when the patient lies flat. This pattern of venous dilatation occurs when blood flow through the superior vena cava (SVC) is obstructed, forcing blood to find alternative routes back to the heart through superficial veins in the upper body.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note the difference between the venous distension seen in SVC obstruction and that seen in \u003Cstrong\u003Eportal hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E (caput medusae). In SVC obstruction, the dilated veins are typically seen on the upper chest, neck, and face, however chronic obstruction can cause further collaterilisation via the abdominal wall veins, dilating longitudinally where they anastamose with the subdiaphragmatic veinous drainage. In contrast, caput medusae, seen in portal hypertension, shows a radial pattern of dilated veins centered around the umbilicus, resembling the head of Medusa. Additionally, in SVC obstruction, patients often present with facial plethora and swelling, which are not typically seen in portal hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECushing\u0027s syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can cause weight gain, central obesity, and facial plethora, but it does not typically cause the prominent venous distension seen in this case. Moreover, the patient\u0027s weight loss and cachectic appearance are inconsistent with Cushing\u0027s syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBudd-Chiari syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, which involves hepatic vein thrombosis, can lead to inferior vena cava obstruction and similar symptoms. However, it usually presents with hepatomegaly and right upper quadrant pain, which are not described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongestive heart failure\u003C/strong\u003E can cause peripheral oedema and occasionally upper body vein dilatation, but it typically presents with other symptoms such as dyspnea, orthopnoea, and lower extremity oedema, which are not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s recent weight loss and general malaise raise concern for an underlying malignancy as a possible cause of the SVC obstruction. Further investigations, including imaging studies such as CT or MRI, would be necessary to determine the underlying cause and extent of the obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Superior vena cava obstruction typically presents with dilated veins on the upper chest, neck, and face, which become more prominent when lying flat.","The pattern of vein distension in superior vena cava obstruction differs from that seen in portal hypertension (caput medusae).","Weight loss and anorexia in conjunction with superior vena cava obstruction raise concern for an underlying malignancy."],"references":["Black A, Tom C. Collateral vasculariszation in chronic superior vena cava syndrome. May Clinic Proceedings. 2023;98(2):348-349. Available at: https://www.mayoclinicproceedings.org/article/S0025-6196(22)00588-2/fulltext","Klein-Weigel P, Elitok S, Ruttloff A, et al. Inferior vena cava-syndrome. Vasa. 2021;50(4):250-264. Available at: https://www.vascular-medicine.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/Klein-Weigel_Editors-Pick.pdf","Oliver TI, Sharma B, John S. Portal Hypertension.In: StatPearls [Online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507718/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35250"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13796"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20738"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20738"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bAtcN9venUSj4S6ai6hMsfcOIWfR9e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bAtcN9venUSj4S6ai6hMsfcOIWfR9e.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":450,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35250"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-05T14:19:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-25T16:39:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6413"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49997"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":nu